I mostly considered if E would make it through the gate with or without the help of either A or B. There were some cases where one of the balls would have hit it on its path, but the other ball pushed it out of the way. That was a factor as well.

More responsible when their own movement directly resulted in E going through/missing gate. If their movement was influenced by the other, they were not as responsible. If E was going one way or the other anyways, not as responsible.

I started to realize toward the end of the trials that the forces/end results could actually be viewed in many different ways.  Especially if you started to think about angles and possible "what ifs" of the different trajectories.
Depending on the initial impact of A and B on E made me decide who was more responsible for E making or missing the gate. This was an interesting experiment.

I thought they were responsible when they were a necessary part of a collision which caused E to go through or not go through. If E was going to go through anyway, I tended to feel the balls were not responsible, except in cases where one knocked it off course and the other was necessary to knock it back on. In some cases, I guessed that if one ball had been absent, a collision with the other ball would have still resulted in the same outcome, in which case I might not have considered a ball responsible even though it was involved. There were times when I wished I could control how many replays I viewed: in several cases, I felt ready to decide after one viewing, but in a few cases I wished I could have viewed once or twice more to better gauge what would have happened without certain events.
They were responsible for E going through or missing the gate whenvever they directly or indirectly caused it to go through.

I looked at whether E would have gone through the gate if neither A nor B interacted with it. I tried to say that A and B were either fully responsible or fully not responsible based upon "if...then" logic. The last experiment seemed more difficult though.

In general I looked at different criteria when determining when a ball was responsible for ball E going through the gate or ball E missing it. Responsible for going through: Ball hits E directly into gate, Ball hits another Ball which hits E directly into the gate, Ball corrects Ball E's trajectory so that it makes it into the gate. Responsible for not going through: If a ball interrupts E's trajectory as it's heading into the gate, or interferes with another Ball that would've hit E and directed it to the right path.

If neither of the balls touched E then neither were responsible, and if E was already going to go into the gate even though it was hit by a ball, then the balls were not responsible.
